text=:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a:Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a:Title: "Done my Homework" Construction%0a:Author: roochis%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 09.04.2021 - 22:38%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a----%0a%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210418-224336-667540#%0a* [-18.04.2021 - 15:43-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210418-224336-667540#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0aSummary: \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aa form of "be" + the participle "done" + a noun phrase = this construction %0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aOriginating in Canadian English, this construction involves three parts: %0a1) A form of "be" (e.g. I'm)%0a%0a2) The participle "done" or "finished" (e.g. "done)%0a%0a3) A noun phrase (e.g. "my homework) %0a%0aTwo examples: %0a- I'm done my homework. %0a- I'm finished my homework. %0a%0aSyntactic Properties %0a1) Degree Modification by "all" %0a%0aOn the surface, "I'm done my homework" resembles verb phrases with a perfect aspect such as "I have done my homework." However, it more closely resembles adjective phrases because they both can be modified by "all." %0a%0aFor example: %0aThe adjective phrase "I'm ready for school" + "all" = "I'm all ready for school" %0a%0aThe construction "I'm done my homework" + "all" = "I'm all done my homework" %0a%0a2) Co-occurrence with perfect aspect%0a%0aThis type of construction can also occur in the perfect aspect. %0a%0aFor example: %0a"I'm done my homework" -> "I'm have been done my homework" %0a%0a3) No leaving the object behind %0aThe object of the construction cannot be separated from "done". %0a%0aFor example: %0aThe phrase "Done though John may be his homework, it won't matter." Is unacceptable. %0a%0a4) Allowed verbs%0aAcross the different dialects, there is a hierarchy of verbs allowed in this construction. The hierarchy is "finished > done > started" %0a%0aIf a speaker accepts "started" in this construction, they will mostly likely accept both "done" and "finished." However, if a speaker accepts "done," they won't necessarily accept "started." %0a%0aSource: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/done-my-homework#syntactic-properties %0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
