diff:1618033137:1618033137:=1,86d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: "Done my Homework" Construction%0a%3c :Author: roochis%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 09.04.2021 - 22:38%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c a form of "be" + the participle "done" + a noun phrase = this construction %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Originating in Canadian English, this construction involves three parts: %0a%3c 1) A form of "be" (e.g. I'm)%0a%3c %0a%3c 2) The participle "done" or "finished" (e.g. "done)%0a%3c %0a%3c 3) A noun phrase (e.g. "my homework) %0a%3c %0a%3c Two examples: %0a%3c - I'm done my homework. %0a%3c - I'm finished my homework. %0a%3c %0a%3c Syntactic Properties %0a%3c 1) Degree Modification by "all" %0a%3c %0a%3c On the surface, "I'm done my homework" resembles verb phrases with a perfect aspect such as "I have done my homework." However, it more closely resembles adjective phrases because they both can be modified by "all." %0a%3c %0a%3c For example: %0a%3c The adjective phrase "I'm ready for school" + "all" = "I'm all ready for school" %0a%3c %0a%3c The construction "I'm done my homework" + "all" = "I'm all done my homework" %0a%3c %0a%3c 2) Co-occurrence with perfect aspect%0a%3c %0a%3c This type of construction can also occur in the perfect aspect. %0a%3c %0a%3c For example: %0a%3c "I'm done my homework" -> "I'm have been done my homework" %0a%3c %0a%3c 3) No leaving the object behind %0a%3c The object of the construction cannot be separated from "done". %0a%3c %0a%3c For example: %0a%3c The phrase "Done though John may be his homework, it won't matter." Is unacceptable. %0a%3c %0a%3c 4) Allowed verbs%0a%3c Across the different dialects, there is a hierarchy of verbs allowed in this construction. The hierarchy is "finished > done > started" %0a%3c %0a%3c If a speaker accepts "started" in this construction, they will mostly likely accept both "done" and "finished." However, if a speaker accepts "done," they won't necessarily accept "started." %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/done-my-homework#syntactic-properties %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
